Comment: Here's an interesting win from one of 4 games I've just finished against this opponent (two league, two tournament).  We finished 2-2 and this was the jammiest win:-)
An interesting variation wherein Black's dsb adopts a more aggressive posture than in the Morphy Defence (4. ...Nf6, 5....d6, 6....Be7), aiming at White's vulnerable f2 square

I adopt a conservative approach, supporting the e4 pawn with my d-pawn rather than with Re1, which leaves f2 poorly defended.  This approach makes White's normally slow Spanish Torture even slower.

Presumably to prevent Bg5, a common enough prophylactic move in the Spanish.
Creating an escape square for my lsb and preparing an eventual d4
Standard approach to pushing White's B back and enabling development of Black's lsb to b7
As usual, I don't retreat my B all the way until I have to.  From b3 this B repays the compliment by attacking f7.
Creating other options for Black's lsb and freeing the Nc6 of its defensive duty in respect of e5.
To prevent the annoying 9...Bg4 and create a hole for the K
Offering to exchange Bishops at the expense of doubled pawns in front of his K.  Such doubled pawns shouldn't be too weakening though because of the mobile d pawn and the resultant half-open f-file.
I decided to accept the exchange as I couldn't see much future for my lsb after 10. Bc2 and I didn't want to allow him to exchange on b3.
Preparing to push the d-pawn, support the option of Be3 and create space for a potential knight manoeuvre Nbd2-f1-g3

Interesting... It creates an opportunity for White to reveal an attack on h5 by moving his knight.  Exactly how to take advantage of this exercised my mind for a while.  As we shall see, I miscalculated.  I can't take advantage of the opportunity immediately because moving my knight also allows ...Bxf2+, now that Black's R occupies the f-file.
